     Sixth report
     Divisions: pass-readers
     Introduction
1.   On 25 October 2021 the House debated our recommendations for the
     introduction of a new procedure for conducting divisions, using pass-readers
     located in the division lobbies and in Prince’s Chamber. Three amendments
     were tabled to this aspect of our report, and after a full debate the Senior
     Deputy Speaker withdrew the motion to agree the report.
2.   After a period of reflection, we published an interim update in our Fifth
     Report, confirming that we remained convinced of the benefits of pass-
     readers, in terms both of speed and accuracy. We acknowledged the concern
     expressed over our initial proposal to dispense with Tellers, and indicated
     that any further proposals we brought forward would retain the role of Teller.
3.   Following a further discussion at our meeting on 18 January 2022, we now
     seek the House’s agreement to these revised proposals for the conduct of
     divisions using pass-readers. We have made these proposals now, with a view
     to commissioning the further work that is required to complete software
     development. This work will take some weeks, and staff are working at speed
     to get the system ready as soon as possible. We propose that the decision
     as to exactly when to deploy pass-reader voting should then be made by
     the House of Lords Commission, taking into account the prevailing public
     health situation.

     The new procedure: key principles
4.   The proposed process for conducting divisions is outlined in Box 1. It is closely
     modelled on the pre-pandemic process, in that it retains the requirement for
     each side to appoint Tellers within three minutes of a vote being called, and
     the principle that if Tellers are not appointed for one side, the question will
     be decided in favour of the other side and the division will be terminated.
5.   The key difference between what we now propose and the pre-pandemic
     process is that members will vote in the lobbies by presenting a valid security
     pass to one of the pass-readers, before leaving the lobbies past the Tellers.
     The pass-readers will then generate the authoritative figure for the number
     of members voting, as well as recording their names. While the Tellers will
     also count members manually, and will validate the result after their return
     to the Table, their figure will only be used as the authority for the result if
     the pass-reader system fails.
6.   This key change is, in our view, essential if the House is to realise the
     benefits of speed, accuracy and security. It follows that in order to vote,
     members will be required to present a valid parliamentary security pass
     that has been registered to the pass-reader system, and we propose that this
     new rule should be reflected in an amended Standing Order. If a member
     mislays their security pass any day-pass issued to them by the Pass Office
     will be automatically registered to the pass-reader system; outside working
     hours such day-passes will be available from Peers’ Entrance. It will be the
     responsibility of each individual member to have their pass with them in
     order to cast their vote and the Clerks at the Table will not have the authority
