      Testing and roll-out
7.    As part of the completion of the system, it will be essential to register all
      members’ passes to the system. 583 members have already registered their
      passes, and staff will ensure that there are opportunities for all other members
      to do so.
8.    It will also be vital to test the system rigorously, to identify any issues, and to
      conduct realistic rehearsals, so that members can familiarise themselves with
      the process before it goes live.

      Location of pass-readers
9.    As part of finalising the system and testing, and if time allows, staff will
      add a fifth pass-reader (re-using the devices previously placed in Prince’s
      Chamber). Once the system is live, staff will monitor traffic in the lobbies,
      and the pass-readers themselves will gather usage data, informing any
      necessary adjustments.
10.   It is proposed that members should not be divided alphabetically: having
      decided to go through either the contents or the not-contents lobby, as the
      case may be, members will be free to use any pass-reader in that lobby.
      Initially we expect the lobbies to be divided into two streams by means of
      rope barriers, to reduce the impact of a temporary blockage at one pass-
      reader, but it will be for members themselves to decide which queue to join.
      Arrangements in the lobbies will of course be kept under review.

      Voting in the ‘wrong lobby’
11.   The pass-readers will be networked, sharing data in real time. This means
      that members will in future be unable to vote in both lobbies. If they attempt
      to do so, they will receive an error message in the second lobby, which will
      tell them to go to the clerk at the Table if they wish to change their vote.
      This process replicates the principle that has hitherto underpinned Standing
      Order 54, though the Standing Order itself will need to be rewritten.
