        Accessibility and members who are blind
12.     The system has been designed to be accessible and clear to users. The first
        pass-reader in each lobby is on a lower stand, making it more easily accessible
        to members using wheelchairs. When a member brings a valid security pass
        close to the pass-reader device located next to the screen, a message will
        appear on the screen with the member’s name, confirming that they have
        voted content or not-content, as the case may be. This message will remain
        on screen for a few seconds before disappearing, or until the next member
        votes, when it will be replaced. The system also emits a ‘bleep’ to confirm
        that a vote has been cast.
13.     Staff have liaised with members who are blind to discuss their use of the
        system. No changes to the system are planned at this stage, but minor
        adaptations may be made following the tests with members to ensure that
        they are able to use the pass-readers. Members who are blind or severely
        visually impaired will also be entitled to cast their vote with the Clerk at the
        Table in the event of any difficulty in using the pass-readers.

        Contingency arrangements
14.     The pass-reader system was introduced in the House of Commons in late
        2021, and has been highly reliable. But it is impossible to completely rule out
        the possibility of either the pass-reader system failing, or of some other issue
        making the pass-reader devices unavailable, such as a power failure.
15.     We propose that in the event of the system failing, the Tellers’ count would be
        authoritative. Staff would record names in each lobby, using paper division
        sheets. The Tellers’ count would be reported to the clerk at the Table, who
        would add the totals for those voting in the Chamber and for eligible members
        voting on PeerHub. Before the system goes live we will also consider whether
        the option of deferred divisions (introduced on a temporary basis as part of
        hybrid House procedures, and still available in the event that the electronic
        voting system fails) should be put on a permanent footing.

        Recommendation
16.     We invite the House:

        •      To agree the process described in Box 1 of this report for the
               conduct of divisions using pass-readers;

        •      To agree the amendments to Standing Orders 52–54 set out in
               Appendix 1;

        •      To mandate the House of Lords Commission, once the pass-
               reader system is ready, to decide when it should be put into
               operation, taking into account the prevailing public health
               situation.

