        Participation of eligible members in oral statements and repeated
        urgent questions
20. Following the House’s agreement to our Fourth Report,2 on 6 December
    the House adopted a new procedure for the remote participation of disabled
    members deemed eligible under SO 24A in oral questions. Under this
    new procedure, the use of speakers’ lists for supplementary questions was
    discontinued, and instead eligible members are now required to notify the
    Government Whips’ Office and their own party or group of their wish to
    ask a supplementary question by the previous working day. It is then for
    the Leader of the House, as part of her responsibility of assisting the House
    during question time, and following consultation with the usual channels, to
    call on Members participating remotely as appropriate.
21.     This change has, in our view, been a success: the Chamber is fuller during oral
        questions, and exchanges are more spontaneous. Data from before and after
        the change also show an increase in the average number of supplementary
        questions asked per oral question.3
22. In our Fourth Report we undertook to “continue to reflect on other types
    of proceeding, such as oral statements, and on the best way to facilitate
    the full participation of eligible disabled Members”. The Government
    Chief Whip has now proposed to us that the procedure for facilitating the
    participation of disabled members deemed eligible under Standing Order
    24A in oral questions should be extended to oral statements and repeated
    urgent questions, whenever there is sufficient notice of such business. We
    support this change, which will mean that eligible disabled members who
    have given notice of their wish to intervene, rather than being called at a
    fixed point in proceedings, will be called on by the Leader of the House
    or her delegate at an appropriate point. As for oral questions, this means
    that remote participants, like those who are physically present, will not be
    guaranteed an opportunity to speak.
